==English==

===Alternative forms===
* [[perservere]]

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fr|en}} {{term|persévérer||lang=la}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|perseverare||to continue steadfastly, persist, persevere|lang=la}}, from {{term|perseverus||very strict or earnest|lang=la}}, from {{term|per||through|lang=la}} + {{term|severus||strict, earnest|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{rhymes|ɪə(ɹ)}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|persever|ing}}

# To [[persist]] steadfastly in pursuit of an [[undertaking]], [[task]], [[journey]], or [[goal]], even if [[hinder]]ed by [[distraction]], [[difficulty]], [[obstacle]]s, or [[discouragement]].
#* '''1606''', [[w:William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]], ''King Lear'', act 3, sc. 5:
#*: I will '''persevere''' in
#*: my course of loyalty, though the conflict be sore
#*: between that and my blood.
#* '''1817''', [[w:Jane Austen|Jane Austen]], ''Persuasion'', ch. 1:
#*: Sir Walter had sought the acquaintance, and though his overtures had not been met with any warmth, he had '''persevered''' in seeking it.
#* {{circa|1918}} [[w:P. G. Wodehouse|P. G. Wodehouse]], "The Agonies of Writing a Musical Comedy":
#*: He is a trifle discouraged, but he '''perseveres'''.

